# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1932-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] The **1932 Chicago Cubs season** was the 61st season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 57th in the National League and the 17th at Wrigley Field.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs finished first in the National League with a record of 90–64, four games ahead of the second place Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] The team was swept four games to none by the New York Yankees in the 1932 World Series.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] "Babe Ruth's called shot" was the home run hit by Babe Ruth in the fifth inning of Game 3 of the 1932 World Series, held on October 1, 1932, at Wrigley Field in Chicago.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] During the at bat, which came against Charlie Root, Ruth made a pointing gesture, which existing film confirms, but the exact nature of his gesture is ambiguous.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] Although neither fully confirmed nor refuted, the story goes that Ruth pointed to the center field bleachers during the at bat.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] It was supposedly a declaration that he would hit a home run to this part of the park.
[src:1932-chicago-cubs-season/1932-chicago-cubs-season] On the next pitch, Ruth hit a home run to center field.
